<i>Why would you talk about that?</i>

256
00:25:00,432 --> 00:25:04,561
They'd be too scared about
being beheaded to fall for you.

257
00:25:05,562 --> 00:25:07,147
You need to watch what you say.

258
00:25:07,230 --> 00:25:09,107
Why would you say that
to someone you just met?

259
00:25:10,567 --> 00:25:11,860
Well, he asked.

260
00:25:11,943 --> 00:25:12,903
So what?

261
00:25:12,986 --> 00:25:16,156
Would you tell him how your poop was
this morning if he asked?

262
00:25:16,239 --> 00:25:17,574
Yes, I'd tell him everything.

263
00:25:19,534 --> 00:25:21,286
Just live alone.

264
00:25:21,370 --> 00:25:23,789
Why are you trying so hard
to love just anyone?

265
00:25:24,581 --> 00:25:27,042
Don't do it. No one will love you.

266
00:25:27,125 --> 00:25:29,002
No man would fall in love with a woman

267
00:25:29,086 --> 00:25:31,421
who says she'd pick up
their lover's severed head.

268
00:25:32,923 --> 00:25:36,593
I just mean, if such a thing happens.
Hypothetically.

269
00:25:36,676 --> 00:25:39,554
Exactly, why are you
imagining that situation?

270
00:25:39,638 --> 00:25:43,266
We don't want to be beheaded.
We don't want to imagine that.

271
00:25:43,850 --> 00:25:47,020
Why did you have to
give him such a gruesome example?

272
00:25:48,271 --> 00:25:50,941
That's the noblest romance?
We're not living in that era.

273
00:25:55,737 --> 00:25:58,824
She's not looking for a boyfriend,
she's looking for a comrade-in-arms.

274
00:25:58,907 --> 00:26:02,160
You must feel so much regret
that you were born in such peaceful times.

275
00:26:02,244 --> 00:26:07,124
You must want to charge at enemies
and risk your life to save the country.

276
00:26:07,207 --> 00:26:09,167
So sitting and eating dinner with a guy

277
00:26:09,251 --> 00:26:12,254
must be terribly dull
and unsatisfying for you, right?

278
00:26:19,761 --> 00:26:20,595
All right, then.

279
00:26:21,763 --> 00:26:23,223
One. Women who run away.

280
00:26:23,306 --> 00:26:24,683
Two. Women who faint.

281
00:26:24,766 --> 00:26:27,602
Three. Women who pick it up.
Which woman do you want?

282
00:26:31,189 --> 00:26:34,526
Which one would you prefer
out of the three?

283
00:26:34,609 --> 00:26:36,695
Hey, which woman are you?

284
00:26:40,282 --> 00:26:42,284
I'd pick it up too if it came to that.

285
00:26:42,993 --> 00:26:44,286
She's a pick-up girl.

286
00:26:44,369 --> 00:26:48,415
Girls who flirt and act all feminine
like Lee Ye-rin would never pick it up.

287
00:26:48,498 --> 00:26:50,417
Those kinds of girls would run away.

288
00:26:51,001 --> 00:26:52,294
Is that love?

289
00:26:54,504 --> 00:26:58,175
So you're saying
that your man should be beheaded.

290
00:26:59,259 --> 00:27:00,135
Hey, Du-hwan.

291
00:27:00,760 --> 00:27:01,928
We need to start a war.

292
00:27:02,012 --> 00:27:04,347
Gi-jeong's man
absolutely must be beheaded.

293
00:27:06,224 --> 00:27:07,434
As long as it's not me.

294
00:27:08,018 --> 00:27:08,894
Oh Du-hwan.

295
00:27:09,519 --> 00:27:12,522
Your name could start a war. Oh Du-hwan.

296
00:27:13,231 --> 00:27:16,109
Yeom Chang-hee. Your name's just as bad.

297
00:27:18,278 --> 00:27:20,238
Mi-jeong, go buy some more alcohol.

298
00:27:22,908 --> 00:27:23,742
No.

299
00:27:24,868 --> 00:27:25,702
No?

300
00:27:27,204 --> 00:27:28,705
Then go borrow some from Gu.

301
00:27:31,666 --> 00:27:33,168
Just go borrow some already.

302
00:27:34,211 --> 00:27:36,671
You bring him food every day.
I'm sure he'll give us some.

303
00:27:36,755 --> 00:27:38,840
Hurry. You and Mr. Gu are close.

304
00:27:41,218 --> 00:27:42,344
As if.

305
00:27:43,303 --> 00:27:44,554
Let's just call it a night.

306
00:27:44,638 --> 00:27:46,765
We're short by just one drink.
Hurry up and go.

307
00:27:49,226 --> 00:27:51,144
There's no alcohol at Mr. Gu's place.
So enough.

308
00:27:51,728 --> 00:27:53,563
Why wouldn't there be when he's a drunk?

309
00:27:54,397 --> 00:27:57,067
Alcoholics never have alcohol stored away.

310
00:27:57,150 --> 00:27:59,027
They just keep two to three bottles.

311
00:27:59,528 --> 00:28:02,239
At first, he thinks,
"Just two bottles today."

312
00:28:02,739 --> 00:28:05,534
"I'll just drink two bottles."
And he only buys two bottles.

313
00:28:05,617 --> 00:28:08,370
Once he finishes them, he just wants more.

314
00:28:08,453 --> 00:28:11,331
So he goes all the way
to the train station to buy more.

315
00:28:11,832 --> 00:28:14,292
It would have been better
if he had started off with four bottles.

316
00:28:14,376 --> 00:28:15,877
But it's always two.

317
00:28:16,628 --> 00:28:18,755
That's how hard it is to be an alcoholic.

318
00:28:20,757 --> 00:28:22,092
You two must be close.

319
00:28:23,093 --> 00:28:24,469
We're next-door neighbors.

320
00:28:26,304 --> 00:28:27,514
Have you guys even talked?

321
00:28:30,058 --> 00:28:30,892
Once.

322
00:28:33,645 --> 00:28:34,688
So, while drinking,

323
00:28:35,313 --> 00:28:37,357
he always goes in
and brings out a new glass.

324
00:28:38,608 --> 00:28:41,778
He always has two or three
shot glasses on the table.

325
00:28:42,696 --> 00:28:44,030
So I asked him why,

326
00:28:44,531 --> 00:28:47,325
and he said he changes glasses
when he gets bored.

327
00:28:51,955 --> 00:28:54,499
What a poor, lonely guy.

328
00:28:55,542 --> 00:28:58,253
I thought he was really cool.

329
00:28:59,588 --> 00:29:00,463
Right.

330
00:29:01,339 --> 00:29:02,632
See, during the day,

331
00:29:03,550 --> 00:29:06,219
he drinks one glass
looking at the window on this side.

332
00:29:07,804 --> 00:29:11,808
When the sun sets, he drinks one glass
looking at the porch over there.

333
00:29:13,560 --> 00:29:14,394
At night,

334
00:29:15,353 --> 00:29:18,231
he drinks one glass
looking at the other window.

335
00:29:19,816 --> 00:29:22,068
He only changes the direction

336
00:29:22,652 --> 00:29:24,946
staying still like this.

337
00:29:27,115 --> 00:29:30,118
It's as if he's standing guard.
Like a neighborhood watch.

338
00:29:35,707 --> 00:29:37,542
Hey, he's not out there today, though.

339
00:29:39,127 --> 00:29:42,172
Come on. It's too hot and humid.

340
00:29:42,255 --> 00:29:45,216
There's no breeze, either.
He's probably inside with the AC on.

341
00:29:48,762 --> 00:29:50,388
Let's call it a night.

342
00:29:51,181 --> 00:29:52,390
Bring those with you.

343
00:29:54,809 --> 00:29:56,019
Should I go over?

344
00:30:26,143 --> 00:30:28,228
This wall is perfect
for catching mosquitoes.

345
00:30:28,729 --> 00:30:30,731
You can see everything. It's so clean.

346
00:30:32,191 --> 00:30:34,693
If a mosquito gets into my room,
I can never find it.

347
00:30:34,777 --> 00:30:37,071
The wallpaper's a mess,
everything's a mess.

348
00:30:40,157 --> 00:30:41,533
How many bottles have you had?

349
00:30:45,704 --> 00:30:48,874
I have the feeling that's the second.

350
00:30:50,876 --> 00:30:55,130
I came because I thought it might
be more fun to have a drinking buddy

351
00:30:55,214 --> 00:30:56,965
than change glasses.

352
00:31:01,470 --> 00:31:03,013
Can I join you?

353
00:31:05,390 --> 00:31:06,767
Where's a glass?

354
00:31:14,817 --> 00:31:15,984
HANJO BANK

355
00:31:33,836 --> 00:31:35,629
Do I look pathetic to you, too?

356
00:31:39,091 --> 00:31:40,676
No way.

357
00:33:03,508 --> 00:33:05,260
YSTAT RESEARCH

358
00:33:07,304 --> 00:33:09,348
Everything else is almost done,

359
00:33:09,431 --> 00:33:11,850
but we don't have enough
single men in their 40s from Gangwon-do.

360
00:33:12,434 --> 00:33:15,062
We won't make it up
with cold calling by 6 p.m.

361
00:33:15,145 --> 00:33:16,355
We should widen the limit.

362
00:33:16,980 --> 00:33:19,358
Let's try for a bit longer.
There's still time.

363
00:33:19,441 --> 00:33:23,278
But it's a long shot. We haven't
gotten anyone in the past two hours.

364
00:33:25,280 --> 00:33:27,199
Let's just widen the limit.

365
00:33:28,909 --> 00:33:29,993
Then…

366
00:33:30,869 --> 00:33:32,120
how about until eight?

367
00:33:32,829 --> 00:33:34,206
Let's try until eight o'clock.

368
00:33:50,097 --> 00:33:51,515
Working overtime again today?

369
00:33:52,099 --> 00:33:53,809
He's making us every day.

370
00:33:54,851 --> 00:33:57,729
That's why he gives out
those lottery tickets so often.

371
00:34:00,023 --> 00:34:03,068
By the way, how did your blind date go?

372
00:34:06,196 --> 00:34:07,197
You know…

373
00:34:07,906 --> 00:34:09,700
We agreed to meet again next time.

374
00:34:11,410 --> 00:34:14,371
Doesn't "next time" usually mean "never"?

375
00:34:19,751 --> 00:34:20,794
I was wondering,

376
00:34:21,628 --> 00:34:23,255
did you get your chompers done?

377
00:34:24,589 --> 00:34:26,758
It's just that they look so straight.

378
00:34:29,803 --> 00:34:32,723
Don't you usually use
the word "chompers" with animals?

379
00:34:33,515 --> 00:34:37,352
For people, we say "teeth."

380
00:34:48,238 --> 00:34:49,990
You can use the word chompers
on people too.

381
00:34:50,657 --> 00:34:54,703
You can say chompers, teeth,
or gnashers. Right?

382
00:34:55,412 --> 00:34:57,372
We can use any of them. What's with her?

383
00:35:16,266 --> 00:35:18,894
Hey. Are you on your way home?

384
00:35:19,853 --> 00:35:20,687
Yes.

385
00:35:21,938 --> 00:35:23,106
Good job today.

386
00:35:23,690 --> 00:35:24,816
You too, Mr. Park.

387
00:35:40,582 --> 00:35:42,626
Can I ask you a question?

388
00:35:43,126 --> 00:35:43,960
Sure.

389
00:35:48,382 --> 00:35:52,636
How many of those lottery tickets
have you given out to women?

390
00:35:54,805 --> 00:35:56,014
I'm sure it's quite a lot.

391
00:35:56,598 --> 00:35:58,016
And not just to women.

392
00:36:00,102 --> 00:36:03,397
Do you know
you've never once given one to me?

393
00:36:12,739 --> 00:36:13,740
No way.

394
00:36:13,824 --> 00:36:15,742
Not even once.

395
00:36:18,703 --> 00:36:20,455
Hold on, wait.

396
00:36:21,373 --> 00:36:22,207
Well…

397
00:36:22,958 --> 00:36:25,085
I'm sorry, that shocked me quite a bit.

398
00:36:26,211 --> 00:36:28,505
I should have been more subtle.

399
00:36:30,465 --> 00:36:31,425
I'm embarrassed.

400
00:36:32,592 --> 00:36:34,636
-I'm so sorry.
-No.

401
00:36:48,984 --> 00:36:49,943
You know,

402
00:36:50,527 --> 00:36:53,530
I've decided to love someone this winter.
Just anyone.

403
00:36:55,157 --> 00:36:56,950
Don't be nervous.

404
00:37:01,121 --> 00:37:04,166
I've been so impatient lately,
I just want to die already.

405
00:37:05,041 --> 00:37:06,710
After 14 years, my job is the same,

406
00:37:06,793 --> 00:37:09,087
the meetings are the same,
and the people are the same,

407
00:37:09,588 --> 00:37:12,841
I curse and get mad the same way.
It's all the same endless repetition.

408
00:37:13,550 --> 00:37:15,302
"Will it be this way until I die?"

409
00:37:15,802 --> 00:37:18,430
"Let's not live like this anymore.
Let's just love anyone."

410
00:37:18,513 --> 00:37:21,516
"Even a relationship
I force myself into could turn into love."

411
00:37:21,600 --> 00:37:24,978
"I'll love him passionately.
I'll make him my whole world."

412
00:37:27,230 --> 00:37:28,064
But…

413
00:37:28,565 --> 00:37:30,108
no one comes near me.

414
00:37:30,734 --> 00:37:32,861
Everyone skips over me, like you.

415
00:37:34,488 --> 00:37:35,822
Well, that was…

416
00:37:37,032 --> 00:37:38,158
A subconscious decision?

417
00:37:39,409 --> 00:37:41,745
I want to know
why it was that you did that.

418
00:37:42,370 --> 00:37:44,331
Why does everybody skip over me?

419
00:37:44,915 --> 00:37:47,959
I'm willing to hear
whatever you have to say

420
00:37:48,043 --> 00:37:50,795
even if it shatters my pride.

421
00:37:51,296 --> 00:37:52,464
Why do you think that is?

422
00:37:54,299 --> 00:37:55,425
Well…

423
00:37:56,051 --> 00:37:59,804
First of all, from my perspective,

424
00:38:00,847 --> 00:38:03,308
the type of woman
a man likes never changes.

425
00:38:03,892 --> 00:38:07,896
Whenever my friends introduce me
to their new girlfriends,

426
00:38:07,979 --> 00:38:10,440
I find that they date people
who are just like their exes.

427
00:38:10,941 --> 00:38:12,234
Men's tastes don't change.

428
00:38:13,652 --> 00:38:18,281
In general, comedians marry comedians,
and actors marry actors, right?

429
00:38:19,533 --> 00:38:21,785
-Well, that's who they see the most.
-No.

430
00:38:21,868 --> 00:38:23,370
That's not the reason.

431
00:38:23,453 --> 00:38:25,580
It's because
they're attracted to those types.

432
00:38:26,373 --> 00:38:29,543
It's whether you prefer
someone who makes you laugh

433
00:38:29,626 --> 00:38:32,003
or someone who makes your heart flutter.

434
00:38:32,671 --> 00:38:33,588
I prefer the latter.

435
00:38:34,464 --> 00:38:35,632
I prefer the latter too.

436
00:38:42,097 --> 00:38:45,725
People who have a lot of dating experience
know what they want.

437
00:38:45,809 --> 00:38:47,352
But those who don't,

438
00:38:47,435 --> 00:38:50,814
don't know what they want
or what type of person they are.

439
00:38:50,897 --> 00:38:54,401
They just want passionate romance
because that's what they hear people want.

440
00:38:54,484 --> 00:38:56,194
But when they finally have it,

441
00:38:56,278 --> 00:38:59,364
many find it
too embarrassing and can't stand it.

442
00:39:00,031 --> 00:39:01,825
It can be embarrassing, but I like it.

443
00:39:01,908 --> 00:39:05,870
When you're embarrassed about something,
it means you find it uncomfortable.

444
00:39:07,247 --> 00:39:08,373
So…

445
00:39:10,542 --> 00:39:15,255
You might be very natural and charming
in a different genre, Ms. Yeom.

446
00:39:15,338 --> 00:39:18,049
Melodrama isn't the only genre
of relationships, right?

447
00:39:18,550 --> 00:39:21,052
There's comedy, surrealism,

448
00:39:21,720 --> 00:39:23,763
thriller… Yes, that's a good one.

449
00:39:23,847 --> 00:39:26,850
What else, slice-of-life? Suspense?
There are so many.

450
00:39:27,434 --> 00:39:32,480
In which genre among those
do you think you'd be most effective?

451
00:39:40,322 --> 00:39:41,781
What are your strengths?

452
00:39:48,788 --> 00:39:50,999
I'm like a Jindo dog.

453
00:39:51,791 --> 00:39:54,961
I stand by my man and never betray him.
I protect him.

454
00:39:55,045 --> 00:39:57,255
And my man must be a real man.

455
00:39:57,339 --> 00:39:59,716
But I don't mean
he has to be all big and burly.

456
00:40:01,551 --> 00:40:04,054
Yes, I have my own idea of masculinity.

457
00:40:04,137 --> 00:40:05,138
A man, yes.

458
00:40:05,972 --> 00:40:07,265
Slice-of-life it is. Yes.

459
00:40:08,058 --> 00:40:09,726
It almost veered toward thriller,

460
00:40:09,809 --> 00:40:11,478
but you're the slice-of-life type.

461
00:40:11,561 --> 00:40:14,856
Many are not really interested
in surprise events or grand gestures.

462
00:40:14,939 --> 00:40:17,817
The most important thing to them
is their attitude toward life.

463
00:40:17,901 --> 00:40:19,277
They look at a person's core.

464
00:40:21,863 --> 00:40:22,864
The core.

465
00:40:23,782 --> 00:40:24,658
Attitude.

466
00:40:25,659 --> 00:40:29,287
Anyway, if you keep that in mind,
you'll usually make the right choice.

467
00:40:30,413 --> 00:40:34,709
And rather than being recklessly
determined to love just anyone,

468
00:40:35,377 --> 00:40:39,464
deciding to go for it
when you meet someone you like

469
00:40:39,547 --> 00:40:40,924
will be far more constructive.

470
00:40:46,471 --> 00:40:49,933
You really are an expert.

471
00:40:50,725 --> 00:40:51,559
Okay.

472
00:40:52,060 --> 00:40:56,064
If I meet a man I like,
I'm going to try to make the first move.

473
00:40:56,648 --> 00:40:57,857
Not just the first move,

474
00:40:58,400 --> 00:40:59,567
but the first confession.

475
00:41:01,945 --> 00:41:04,447
That's so embarrassing though.

476
00:41:04,531 --> 00:41:05,907
My mom always says,

477
00:41:05,990 --> 00:41:09,577
"A house and spouse will come
to you when the time is right."

478
00:41:09,661 --> 00:41:12,122
You'll find one when the time is right.

479
00:41:12,789 --> 00:41:14,457
-Will he?
-He will.

480
00:41:16,459 --> 00:41:17,502
Okay.

481
00:41:19,587 --> 00:41:23,091
I feel like I need to give you
a fortune-teller's fee or something.

482
00:41:23,174 --> 00:41:24,175
No.

483
00:41:36,938 --> 00:41:39,691
If I go this way, I can get home faster.

484
00:41:40,400 --> 00:41:41,484
Get home safe.

485
00:41:42,068 --> 00:41:44,738
You must really not be
interested in me at all.

486
00:41:44,821 --> 00:41:46,573
You can't wait to go home.

487
00:41:48,158 --> 00:41:50,285
No, I'm just kidding.

488
00:41:50,368 --> 00:41:52,620
-Let's go together.
-No, go ahead.

489
00:41:52,704 --> 00:41:54,497
-It's fine. Go ahead.
-All right.

490
00:41:54,581 --> 00:41:58,084
-See you tomorrow.
-Go on, off you go. Go ahead. Go.

491
00:41:58,835 --> 00:41:59,753
See you tomorrow.

492
00:42:29,365 --> 00:42:33,953
SOMETHING GOOD WILL HAPPEN TO YOU TODAY

493
00:42:35,747 --> 00:42:37,624
Something good, my foot.

494
00:43:11,991 --> 00:43:13,117
I'm going to go.

495
00:43:14,452 --> 00:43:16,788
Hey, use the restroom before you go.

496
00:43:18,456 --> 00:43:19,290
I'm fine.

497
00:43:19,874 --> 00:43:22,126
Do as I say.
It's a long way back to Seoul.

498
00:43:22,210 --> 00:43:24,170
I just wanted to try coming here once.

499
00:43:27,757 --> 00:43:29,175
I came here for a change!

500
00:43:29,759 --> 00:43:31,594
To your neighborhood, Dangmi Station!

501
00:43:33,304 --> 00:43:34,597
It's nothing special.

502
00:43:52,699 --> 00:43:55,285
Even if you need to pee, hold it.
This is the last train.

503
00:43:55,368 --> 00:43:57,412
Hold it until you get to Seoul.

504
00:44:46,002 --> 00:44:47,003
I'm home.

505
00:44:47,086 --> 00:44:48,671
Mom and Dad aren't here.

506
00:44:49,172 --> 00:44:50,340
Where are they?

507
00:44:50,423 --> 00:44:51,507
At a funeral.

508
00:44:52,383 --> 00:44:53,593
Who passed away?

509
00:44:54,093 --> 00:44:54,969
Mom's uncle.

510
00:45:07,690 --> 00:45:10,818
